    <h1>💻 Example Controller Explained</h1>

    <p>
        Let's look at a simple example of a controller and understand what each part does.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>🔹 Example Controller</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">C# Controller Example</div>
        <div class="code-content">
            <pre><code class="language-csharp">
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

namespace MyApp.Controllers
{
    public class HomeController : Controller
    {
        // Action for the home page
        public IActionResult Index()
        {
            return View(); // Sends the Index.cshtml page to the browser
        }

        // Action for the About page
        public IActionResult About()
        {
            ViewData["Message"] = "This is the About page."; // Pass data to the view
            return View(); // Sends the About.cshtml page to the browser
        }
    }
}
            </code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>🔹 What This Code Does</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;</strong> → Imports MVC library for controllers & views.</li>
        <li><strong>namespace MyApp.Controllers</strong> → Organizes your controllers in a namespace.</li>
        <li><strong>public class HomeController : Controller</strong> → Defines a controller class inheriting from Controller.</li>
        <li><strong>public IActionResult Index()</strong> → Handles requests for the home page.</li>
        <li><strong>return View();</strong> → Returns the view (web page) to the browser.</li>
        <li><strong>public IActionResult About()</strong> → Handles requests for the About page.</li>
        <li><strong>ViewData["Message"]</strong> → Passes data to the view.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>🔹 How It Works Step by Step</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>1️⃣ User goes to <code>/Home/Index</code> → <strong>Index</strong> action runs → Index View is displayed.</li>
        <li>2️⃣ User goes to <code>/Home/About</code> → <strong>About</strong> action runs → About View is displayed with the message.</li>
        <li>3️⃣ The controller decides which page and data to show → acts as a bridge between user and app.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>✅ In short:</strong> Controllers manage requests, interact with models if needed, and return the appropriate views or data.</p>

